{"title_page": "May Kaftan-Kassim", "text_new": "{{short description|Iraqi radio astronomer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = May Kaftan-Kassim\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = May Arif Kaftan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1928}}\n| birth_place        = Iraq\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Astronomer\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''May Arif Kaftan-Kassim''' (born 1928), also known as '''May A. Kaftan''', is an Iraqi radio astronomer. She trained at [[Harvard University]], and advised on the creation of the [[Erbil Observatory]] in Iraq in the 1970s.\n\n== Early life ==\nMay Arif Kaftan came from a \"fairly conventional, very religious Muslim family,\" by her own account. Her father was a government official.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034352/may_kaftan_1979/|title=A Woman Astronomer's View from Iraq|last=Hendrix|first=Kathleen|date=December 2, 1979|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 28, 2019|page=145|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She attended the [[University of Manchester]] as an undergraduate and graduate student, on a scholarship for Iraqi students in the sciences.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EeqKDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA45&dq=May%20Kaftan%20Kassim&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q=May%20Kaftan%20Kassim&f=false|title=Space Science and the Arab World: Astronauts, Observatories and Nationalism in the Middle East|last=Determann|first=J\u00f6rg Matthias|date=January 29, 2018|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9781786733528|location=|pages=19, 39, 45\u201346|language=en}}</ref> She completed her doctoral studies in astronomy at [[Radcliffe College]] in 1958, with a dissertation titled ''A study of neutral hydrogen in a region in Cygnus''.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=A study of neutral hydrogen in a region in Cygnus|date=1958|language=English|first=May Arif|last=Kaftan Kassim|oclc=22975232}}</ref> American astronomers [[Nan Dieter-Conklin]] and [[Frank Drake]] were her classmates in astronomy at Harvard; they all finished in the same year, and all studied under [[Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin]].<ref>[https://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/4573 Interview of Nan Dieter-Conklin] by David DeVorkin on 1977 July 19, Niels Bohr Library & Archives, American Institute of Physics.<br /></ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKaftan-Kassim worked at the [[National Radio Astronomy Observatory]] in West Virginia, from 1964 to 1966.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1968, she attended the [[United Nations]] Conference on the Exploration and Peaceful Uses of Outer Space ([[United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space|COPUOS]]), in Vienna, informally representing Iraq.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was on staff at the [[Dudley Observatory]] at the [[University at Albany, SUNY|State University of New York at Albany]] in the early 1970s.<ref>Erkes, J. W. & Weinberg, J. L. (1975). [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1975BAAS....7...31E \"Dudley Observatory and State University of New York at Albany (SUNYA), Albany, New York\"] ''Bulletin of the Astronomical Society'' 7: 31.</ref> While attending the annual [[International Union of Radio Science|URSI]] meeting in Washington D.C. in 1981, Kaftan-Kassim gave an oral history interview for the National Radio Astronomy Observatory archives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrao.edu/archives/Sullivan/sullivan_interviewee_kaftankassim.shtml|title=Papers of Woodruff T. Sullivan III|website=www.nrao.edu|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> She was a visiting professor of astronomy at [[Agnes Scott College]], 1983-1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agnesscott.edu/physics/faculty/emeriti-faculty/may-kaftan-kassim.html|title=May Kaftan-Kassim|last=|first=|date=|website=Agnes Scott College Department of Physics|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034253/may_kaftankassim_1983/|title=Lectures|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1983|work=The Atlanta Constitution|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Erbil Observatory.jpg|alt=An observatory on a mountain, against a blue sky and a white cloud.|thumb|Erbil Observatory, which Kaftan-Kassim helped launch in the 1970s.]]\nKaftan-Kassim helped establish the astronomy program at the University of Baghdad, advising on texts and hiring.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034834/may_kaftankassim_1964/|title=Office Opened by Dr. Kassim|last=|first=|date=March 4, 1964|work=The Bridgeport Post|access-date=May 28, 2019|page=14|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She returned to Baghdad in the mid-1970s to advise on the construction of Iraq's National Astronomical Observatory,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034131/may_kaftankassim_1974/|title=Albany Teacher Invited to Iraq|last=|first=|date=May 9, 1974|work=The Post-Star|access-date=May 28, 2019|page=16|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> near [[Erbil]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1983/0321/032147.html|title=Iraq grapples with sandy solar collectors|date=March 21, 1983|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=May 28, 2019|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> and was a project manager there, before she lost her position in 1981 in a shifting political context.<ref name=\":1\" /> \"I came back with the understanding that it would be six months here, six months there,\" she explained to an American newspaper in 1979, \"but there is so much to do I can't go back to the States.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> She spent some time doing research at the [[Byurakan Observatory|Byurakan Astrophysical Observatory]] in the Soviet Union.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3DqOARyWib4C&lpg=PA169&dq=Kaftan%20astronomy&pg=PA169#v=onepage&q=Kaftan%20astronomy&f=false|title=A Brief History of Radio Astronomy in the USSR: A Collection of Scientific Essays|last=Braude|first=S. Y.|last2=Dubinskii|first2=B. A.|last3=Kaidanovskii|first3=N. L.|last4=Kardashev|first4=N. S.|last5=Kobrin|first5=M. M.|last6=Kuzmin|first6=A. D.|last7=Molchanov|first7=A. P.|last8=Pariiskii|first8=Yu N.|last9=Rzhiga|first9=O. N.|date=March 14, 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789400728332|location=|pages=169|language=en}}</ref> She did, eventually, return to the United States to live.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/2523/|title=May A. Kaftan|last=|first=|date=2017|website=International Astronomical Union Member Directory|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The [[American Astronomical Society]] listed her as a member for over 60 years in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aas.org/posts/news/2017/02/aas-member-anniversaries-2017|title=AAS Member Anniversaries in 2017|last=Tinch|first=Crystal M.|date=February 22, 2017|website=American Astronomical Society|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nResearch publications by Kaftan-Kassim included \"Measurements of the 1.9 cm Thermal Radio Emission from Mercury\" (''Nature'' 1967),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaftan-Kassim|first=M. A.|last2=Kellermann|first2=K. I.|date=January 1967|title=Measurements of the 1.9 cm Thermal Radio Emission from Mercury|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=213|issue=5073|pages=272\u2013273|doi=10.1038/213272a0|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> \"A Survey of High-Frequency Radio Radiation from Planetary Nebulae\" (''Astrophysical Journal'' 1969),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaftan-Kassim|first=May A.|date=February 1, 1969|title=A Survey of High-Frequency Radio Radiation from Planetary Nebulae|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=155|pages=469|doi=10.1086/149882|issn=0004-637X|bibcode=1969ApJ...155..469K}}</ref> \"High Frequency Radio Observations of the Stephan's Quintet Region\" (''Nature'' 1975),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sistla|first=Gopal|last2=Sulentic|first2=Jack W.|last3=Kaftan-Kassim|first3=May A.|date=1975|title=High frequency radio observations of the Stephan's Quintet region|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=253|issue=5488|pages=176\u2013177|doi=10.1038/253176a0|issn=1476-4687}}</ref>  \"Extinction and Radio Structure of IC 2149\" (''Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society'' 1977),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sistla|first=G.|last2=Kaftan-Kassim|first2=M. A.|date=March 1, 1977|title=Extinction and radio structure of IC 2149|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|language=en|volume=178|issue=3|pages=325\u2013328|doi=10.1093/mnras/178.3.325|issn=0035-8711}}</ref> and \"A Radio Continuum Survey of Isolated Pairs of Galaxies\" (''Astronomical Journal'' 1978).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stocke|first=J. T.|last2=Tifft|first2=W. G.|last3=Kaftan-Kassim|first3=M. A.|date=March 1978|title=A radio continuum survey of isolated pairs of galaxies|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=83|pages=322|doi=10.1086/112209|bibcode=1978AJ.....83..322S}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKaftan married pediatrician Sami El-Sheikh Kassim; they separated in the 1970s.<ref name=\":0\" /> Their son Namir E. Kassim was born in Baghdad; he also became a radio astronomer in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://physics.unm.edu/cart/kassim.php|title=Namir Kassim|last=|first=|date=|website=University of New Mexico, Department of Physics and Astronomy, Center for Astrophysical Research and Technologies|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/2523/ May A. Kaftan's IAU listing], updated 2017.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaftan-Kassim, May}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Iraqi women academics]]\n[[Category:Iraqi scientists]]\n[[Category:Women astronomers]]\n[[Category:Radio astronomers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iraqi radio astronomer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = May Kaftan-Kassim\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = May Arif Kaftan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1928}}\n| birth_place        = Iraq\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Astronomer\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''May Arif Kaftan-Kassim''' (born 1928), also known as '''May A. Kaftan''', is an Iraqi radio astronomer. She trained at [[Harvard University]], and advised on the creation of  [[Erbil Observatory]] in Iraq in the 1970s.\n\n== Early life ==\nMay Arif Kaftan came from a \"fairly conventional, very religious Muslim family,\" by her own account. Her father was a government official.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034352/may_kaftan_1979/|title=A Woman Astronomer's View from Iraq|last=Hendrix|first=Kathleen|date=December 2, 1979|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 28, 2019|page=145|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She attended the [[University of Manchester]] as an undergraduate and graduate student, on a scholarship for Iraqi students in the sciences.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EeqKDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA45&dq=May%20Kaftan%20Kassim&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q=May%20Kaftan%20Kassim&f=false|title=Space Science and the Arab World: Astronauts, Observatories and Nationalism in the Middle East|last=Determann|first=J\u00f6rg Matthias|date=January 29, 2018|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9781786733528|location=|pages=19, 39, 45\u201346|language=en}}</ref> She completed her doctoral studies in astronomy at [[Radcliffe College]] in 1958, with a dissertation titled ''A study of neutral hydrogen in a region in Cygnus''.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=A study of neutral hydrogen in a region in Cygnus|date=1958|language=English|first=May Arif|last=Kaftan Kassim|oclc=22975232}}</ref> American astronomers [[Nan Dieter-Conklin]] and [[Frank Drake]] were her classmates in astronomy at Harvard; they all finished in the same year, and all studied under [[Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin]].<ref>[https://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/4573 Interview of Nan Dieter-Conklin] by David DeVorkin on 1977 July 19, Niels Bohr Library & Archives, American Institute of Physics.<br /></ref>\n\n== Career ==\nKaftan-Kassim worked at the [[National Radio Astronomy Observatory]] in West Virginia, from 1964 to 1966.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1968, she attended the [[United Nations]] Conference on the Exploration and Peaceful Uses of Outer Space ([[United Nations Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space|COPUOS]]), in Vienna, informally representing Iraq.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was on staff at the [[Dudley Observatory]] at the [[University at Albany, SUNY|State University of New York at Albany]] in the early 1970s.<ref>Erkes, J. W. & Weinberg, J. L. (1975). [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1975BAAS....7...31E \"Dudley Observatory and State University of New York at Albany (SUNYA), Albany, New York\"] ''Bulletin of the Astronomical Society'' 7: 31.</ref> While attending the annual [[International Union of Radio Science|URSI]] meeting in Washington D.C. in 1981, Kaftan-Kassim gave an oral history interview for the National Radio Astronomy Observatory archives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrao.edu/archives/Sullivan/sullivan_interviewee_kaftankassim.shtml|title=Papers of Woodruff T. Sullivan III|website=www.nrao.edu|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> She was a visiting professor of astronomy at [[Agnes Scott College]], 1983-1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agnesscott.edu/physics/faculty/emeriti-faculty/may-kaftan-kassim.html|title=May Kaftan-Kassim|last=|first=|date=|website=Agnes Scott College Department of Physics|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034253/may_kaftankassim_1983/|title=Lectures|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1983|work=The Atlanta Constitution|access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Erbil Observatory.jpg|alt=An observatory on a mountain, against a blue sky and a white cloud.|thumb|Erbil Observatory, which Kaftan-Kassim helped launch in the 1970s.]]\nKaftan-Kassim helped establish the astronomy program at the University of Baghdad, advising on texts and hiring.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034834/may_kaftankassim_1964/|title=Office Opened by Dr. Kassim|last=|first=|date=March 4, 1964|work=The Bridgeport Post|access-date=May 28, 2019|page=14|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> She returned to Baghdad in the mid-1970s to advise on the construction of Iraq's National Astronomical Observatory,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32034131/may_kaftankassim_1974/|title=Albany Teacher Invited to Iraq|last=|first=|date=May 9, 1974|work=The Post-Star|access-date=May 28, 2019|page=16|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> near [[Erbil]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1983/0321/032147.html|title=Iraq grapples with sandy solar collectors|date=March 21, 1983|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=May 28, 2019|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> and was a project manager there, before she lost her position in 1981 in a shifting political context.<ref name=\":1\" /> \"I came back with the understanding that it would be six months here, six months there,\" she explained to an American newspaper in 1979, \"but there is so much to do I can't go back to the States.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> She spent some time doing research at the [[Byurakan Observatory|Byurakan Astrophysical Observatory]] in the Soviet Union.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3DqOARyWib4C&lpg=PA169&dq=Kaftan%20astronomy&pg=PA169#v=onepage&q=Kaftan%20astronomy&f=false|title=A Brief History of Radio Astronomy in the USSR: A Collection of Scientific Essays|last=Braude|first=S. Y.|last2=Dubinskii|first2=B. A.|last3=Kaidanovskii|first3=N. L.|last4=Kardashev|first4=N. S.|last5=Kobrin|first5=M. M.|last6=Kuzmin|first6=A. D.|last7=Molchanov|first7=A. P.|last8=Pariiskii|first8=Yu N.|last9=Rzhiga|first9=O. N.|date=March 14, 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9789400728332|location=|pages=169|language=en}}</ref> She did, eventually, return to the United States to live.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/2523/|title=May A. Kaftan|last=|first=|date=2017|website=International Astronomical Union Member Directory|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The [[American Astronomical Society]] listed her as a member for over 60 years in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aas.org/posts/news/2017/02/aas-member-anniversaries-2017|title=AAS Member Anniversaries in 2017|last=Tinch|first=Crystal M.|date=February 22, 2017|website=American Astronomical Society|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nResearch publications by Kaftan-Kassim included \"Measurements of the 1.9 cm Thermal Radio Emission from Mercury\" (''Nature'' 1967),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaftan-Kassim|first=M. A.|last2=Kellermann|first2=K. I.|date=January 1967|title=Measurements of the 1.9 cm Thermal Radio Emission from Mercury|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=213|issue=5073|pages=272\u2013273|doi=10.1038/213272a0|issn=0028-0836}}</ref> \"A Survey of High-Frequency Radio Radiation from Planetary Nebulae\" (''Astrophysical Journal'' 1969),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kaftan-Kassim|first=May A.|date=February 1, 1969|title=A Survey of High-Frequency Radio Radiation from Planetary Nebulae|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=155|pages=469|doi=10.1086/149882|issn=0004-637X|bibcode=1969ApJ...155..469K}}</ref> \"High Frequency Radio Observations of the Stephan's Quintet Region\" (''Nature'' 1975),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sistla|first=Gopal|last2=Sulentic|first2=Jack W.|last3=Kaftan-Kassim|first3=May A.|date=1975|title=High frequency radio observations of the Stephan's Quintet region|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=253|issue=5488|pages=176\u2013177|doi=10.1038/253176a0|issn=1476-4687}}</ref>  \"Extinction and Radio Structure of IC 2149\" (''Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society'' 1977),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sistla|first=G.|last2=Kaftan-Kassim|first2=M. A.|date=March 1, 1977|title=Extinction and radio structure of IC 2149|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|language=en|volume=178|issue=3|pages=325\u2013328|doi=10.1093/mnras/178.3.325|issn=0035-8711}}</ref> and \"A Radio Continuum Survey of Isolated Pairs of Galaxies\" (''Astronomical Journal'' 1978).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stocke|first=J. T.|last2=Tifft|first2=W. G.|last3=Kaftan-Kassim|first3=M. A.|date=March 1978|title=A radio continuum survey of isolated pairs of galaxies|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=83|pages=322|doi=10.1086/112209|bibcode=1978AJ.....83..322S}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKaftan married pediatrician Sami El-Sheikh Kassim; they separated in the 1970s.<ref name=\":0\" /> Their son Namir E. Kassim was born in Baghdad; he also became a radio astronomer in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://physics.unm.edu/cart/kassim.php|title=Namir Kassim|last=|first=|date=|website=University of New Mexico, Department of Physics and Astronomy, Center for Astrophysical Research and Technologies|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.iau.org/administration/membership/individual/2523/ May A. Kaftan's IAU listing], updated 2017.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaftan-Kassim, May}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Iraqi women academics]]\n[[Category:Iraqi scientists]]\n[[Category:Women astronomers]]\n[[Category:Radio astronomers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Paradise Chronicle", "label": "safe", "comment": "the erbil observatory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/May_Kaftan-Kassim"}
